{{fr-noun|f|mesdemoiselles}}

# {{lb|fr|dated}} [[Miss]]; {{n-g|A form of address or title for an unmarried woman}}
# [[Miss]]; {{n-g|A form of address or title for a young woman, regardless of marital status}}
## {{lb|fr|Quebec}} [[Miss]]; {{n-g|as a form of address or title for a young girl}}

====Usage notes====
* ''Mademoiselle'' has been on the decline as a title for unmarried women since the 1970s, and its usage is restricted to addressing young women if their age is to be highlighted. In Quebec, this usage is restricted even further, only being used for young girls or women who want to be referred by it.<ref>{{cite-web|author=Office québécois de la langue française|title=Les noms ''madame'' et ''mademoiselle''|url=https://vitrinelinguistique.oqlf.gouv.qc.ca/23634/le-vocabulaire/tours-dhorizon-et-autres-explications/usages/les-noms-madame-et-mademoiselle|work=Banque de dépannage linguistique|accessdate=June 24, 2024}}</ref> {{m|fr|madame|Madame}} is used and preferred to refer to women regardless of marital status.
* After being regarded as sexist, ''mademoiselle'' has been banned or discouraged in official documents in the following French-speaking regions:
** Switzerland since 1973
** Quebec since 1976<ref>{{cite-journal|fr|journal=Slate|url=https://www.slate.fr/story/44797/mademoiselle-france-ringard-etats-unis-quebec|title=Comment le «mademoiselle» est devenu ringard aux Etats-Unis et au Québec|trans-title=How "mademoiselle" became outdated in the U.S. and in Quebec|author=Claire Levenson|date=October 11, 2011}}</ref>
** The French Community of Belgium since December 13, 1993<ref>{{cite-web|fr|url=http://www.lettresetlivre.cfwb.be/index.php?id=62|title=Arrêté du Gouvernement de la Communauté française du 13 décembre 1993 établissant les règles de féminisation des noms de métier, fonction, grade ou titre|date=December 13, 1993|author=Fédération Wallonie-Bruxelles|work=Service Général des Lettres et du Livre}}</ref>
** France since February 21, 2012<ref>{{cite-journal|en|author=Scott Sayare|title=‘Mademoiselle’ Exits Official France|work=The New York Times|date=2012-02-22|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/23/world/europe/france-drops-mademoiselle-from-official-use.html|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite-web|en|title=Mademoiselle is no longer an official French woman|work=Reuters|date=2012-02-23|titleurl=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-mademoiselle-idUSTRE81M1DR20120223}}</ref>
** Luxembourg since March 9, 2012<ref>{{cite-journal|fr|url=https://www.lessentiel.lu/fr/story/mademoiselle-disparait-au-luxembourg-783693299545|author=MC|date=March 30, 2012|title=«Mademoiselle» disparaît au Luxembourg|trans-title="Mademoiselle" disappears in Luxembourg|journal=L'essentiel}}</ref>
* The form {{m|fr|madelle}} (a {{glossary|blend}} of {{m|fr|madame}} and ''mademoiselle'') has been suggested as a replacement, but never caught on. Instead, ''madame'' is used regardless of marital status.

